Redescribed by Costa &amp; Lacerda (1988).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A2443683FFBD411EFF2CAE71E1ADFD79" blockId="9.[164,779,570,653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">
<emphasis id="908FEA91FFBD411EFF2CAE71E276FDBB" box="[164,309,570,591]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">Distribution:</emphasis>
Estrela and Roncador river basins: two small, isolated basins draining into Guanabara bay, 
<collectingRegion id="603FF861FFBD411EFF2CAE3CE2D1FD78" box="[164,402,631,653]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">Rio de Janeiro state</collectingRegion>
, south-eastern 
<collectingCountry id="DAEC7613FFBD411EFDCFAE3CE1CEFD79" box="[583,653,631,653]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="3AC02A06FFBD411EFD17AE3CE1A2FD79" box="[671,737,631,653]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="4.[144,223,1853,1872]" captionTargetBox="[368,1198,1236,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-333@4.[367,1199,1235,1824]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 5. Geographical distribution of Leptolebias in Rio de Janeiro state, south-eastern Brazil: 1, L. marmoratus, L. splendens, and L. opalescens; 2, L. marmoratus and L. opalescens; 3, L. splendens; 4, L. citrinipinnis." pageId="9" pageNumber="156">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A2443683FFBD411EFF2CAE8DE1A6FB7C" blockId="9.[164,779,710,1160]" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">
<emphasis id="908FEA91FFBD411EFF2CAE8DE197FD2F" box="[164,724,710,731]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">
Habitat and conservation: 
<taxonomicName id="65FB4D00FFBD411EFE53AE8DE197FD2F" baseAuthorityName="Myers" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[475,724,710,731]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Leptolebias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="156" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">Leptolebias splendens</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was a common fish in the Estrela river basin until 1944 (A. L. Carvalho and H. S. Lopez, pers. comm.), when the region still contained well-preserved forests near and along the old road Rio–Petrópolis. After this time, both the forest and 
<taxonomicName id="65FB4D00FFBD411EFE06AF14E15FFC80" baseAuthorityName="Myers" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[398,540,863,884]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Leptolebias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="156" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis id="908FEA91FFBD411EFE06AF14E15FFC80" box="[398,540,863,884]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">L. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
disappeared. It was rediscovered 41 years later in temporary pools within a well-preserved forest belonging to a group of Brazilian scouts (Costa &amp; Lacerda, 1988), in the Roncador river basin. However, although the forest is still well preserved today, 
<taxonomicName id="65FB4D00FFBD411EFE14AFB3E16AFBF9" baseAuthorityName="Myers" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[412,553,1016,1037]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Leptolebias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="156" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis id="908FEA91FFBD411EFE14AFB3E16AFBF9" box="[412,553,1016,1037]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">L. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been found since 1987. Part of the stream draining the forest was diverted to a neighbouring fish farm, which apparently altered the water levels of aquatic bodies in the forest. 
<taxonomicName id="65FB4D00FFBD411EFF7DA839E2ACFB73" baseAuthorityName="Myers" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[245,495,1138,1159]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Leptolebias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="156" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis id="908FEA91FFBD411EFF7DA839E2ACFB73" box="[245,495,1138,1159]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">Leptolebias splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may now be extinct.
</paragraph>
